				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Young Bards Today(cont)<a name="7279"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 14 03 11:05 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Study Reed's Spreadsheet, look at the DPS you do vs others, and compare with the instrument buff bonuses you can do with an instrument switching twist.
<br />

<br />
As a general rule of thumb....if you are significantly affecting 3 or more group members (ie melee's with Chant of Battle). With a certain song, that has an instrument mod, and you have at least combine instruments, you may be doing better instrument twisting (and yes switching instruments while you twist) than joining in melee. 
<br />

<br />
If you have spent pp/quested instruments before weapons (not a bad idea) you may even be more effective  using instrument mods on 2.
<br />

<br />
Having said that, not every group will understand why you aren't swinging away (and if there is no aggro/stun problem, you should be doing so barehanded). Hastes don't benefit from instrument mods/amp....but the accompanying stats do.
<br />

<br />
Ditto for crowd control, especially if you are using a charm (who's DPS could well out pace any group members).
<br />

<br />
Do both and see which is more enjoyable/rewarding/quicker?
<br />

<br />
Most 40/50 ish bards can do more damage with a 3 dot twist, (AoE or single target DoT) than they can melee...but a bard's DPS  is certainly not the whole picture in groups (certainly the DPS they contribute by buffing/hasting others is important).</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
